---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base title="Projects">
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="eyebrow">Projects</div>
    <h1>What I'm building</h1>
    <p class="hero-lede muted">
      A small set of proof-oriented threads, product work, personal systems,
      and infrastructure that show how I think in public. The common thread is
      simple: real AI value appears when runtime, memory, and deployment hold up.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <span class="section-label">Primary threads</span>

    <div class="project-card" id="sleephub">
      <h3>SleepHub</h3>
      <p>
        Ambient, bedside AI product work for autonomous sleep coaching and
        tracking. This is where product, device integration, sleep analysis,
        and real-world user loops meet. It is the clearest public signal of my
        applied AI work and my bias toward systems that have to earn trust over time.
      </p>
      <div class="tag-row">
        <span class="tag">sleep</span>
        <span class="tag">ambient AI</span>
        <span class="tag">product</span>
        <span class="tag">deployment</span>
      </div>
      <div class="project-links">
        <a href="https://asleep.ai" target="_blank" rel="noopener">asleep.ai</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="project-card" id="knowledge-os">
      <h3>Knowledge OS</h3>
      <p>
        A markdown-first personal operating system for memory, retrieval, and
        public expression. Files as source of truth, agents as readers and
        writers, git as history. It is both a working system and a statement
        about inspectability, explicit memory, and how AI should integrate with real workflows.
      </p>
      <div class="tag-row">
        <span class="tag">knowledge</span>
        <span class="tag">memory</span>
        <span class="tag">agents</span>
        <span class="tag">markdown</span>
        <span class="tag">public layer</span>
      </div>
      <div class="project-links">
        <a href="/direction">Direction</a>
        <a href="https://github.com/keenranger" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="project-card" id="agent-infra">
      <h3>Agent infrastructure</h3>
      <p>
        Runtime correctness, memory continuity, and workflow tooling for
        human-AI collaboration. Multi-agent orchestration, session handling,
        tool contracts, and guardrails encoded into the environment itself.
        The interesting work is what the system does when context is partial,
        state drifts, or humans interrupt.
      </p>
      <div class="tag-row">
        <span class="tag">agents</span>
        <span class="tag">infrastructure</span>
        <span class="tag">runtime</span>
        <span class="tag">workflow</span>
      </div>
      <div class="project-links">
        <a href="/direction">Why this matters</a>
        <a href="https://github.com/keenranger" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <span class="section-label">Early explorations</span>

    <div class="project-card" id="patient-family-sharing">
      <h3>Patient&ndash;family record sharing</h3>
      <p>
        A lightweight digital health layer for the period after a hospital
        visit. The patient records what they were told &mdash; appointments,
        instructions, preparation items &mdash; and chooses to share those
        notes with a family member or care companion they designate, so both
        sides can stay on the same page about what comes next. Scoped
        deliberately to patient-led record sharing, preparation, and
        communication support outside the hospital &mdash; not medical
        judgment, not triage. Early stage; being shaped with real patient and
        family input before any code commits to a direction.
      </p>
      <div class="tag-row">
        <span class="tag">digital health</span>
        <span class="tag">patient-led</span>
        <span class="tag">post-visit</span>
        <span class="tag">record sharing</span>
        <span class="tag">exploration</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <span class="section-label">Public utilities &amp; experiments</span>

    <div class="project-card" id="open-wall">
      <h3>Open Wall</h3>
      <p>
        Multi-angle indoor room reconstruction powered by OpenAI
        <code>gpt-image-2</code>. An early experiment in turning image models
        into a spatial reconstruction workflow rather than a one-off image generator.
      </p>
      <div class="tag-row">
        <span class="tag">image models</span>
        <span class="tag">spatial AI</span>
        <span class="tag">experiment</span>
      </div>
      <div class="project-links">
        <a href="https://github.com/keenranger/open-wall" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="project-card" id="workflow-tools">
      <h3>Workflow tools</h3>
      <p>
        Small public tools around real workflows: a Toss Securities CLI, a
        Google Timeline visualizer, and dotfiles for environment management.
        These are deliberately practical systems: narrow enough to inspect,
        useful enough to keep.
      </p>
      <div class="tag-row">
        <span class="tag">CLI</span>
        <span class="tag">personal data</span>
        <span class="tag">workflow</span>
        <span class="tag">dev environment</span>
      </div>
      <div class="project-links">
        <a href="https://github.com/keenranger/tossinvest-cli" target="_blank" rel="noopener">tossinvest-cli</a>
        <a href="https://github.com/keenranger/google-timeline-visualizer" target="_blank" rel="noopener">google-timeline-visualizer</a>
        <a href="https://github.com/keenranger/dotfiles" target="_blank" rel="noopener">dotfiles</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <p>
      <a class="arrow-link" href="/direction">Read why these, and where they're going</a>
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>
